It’s not just what you do, but it’s how you do it. 

Intention Matters and It. Matters. A. Lot.

Especially if your goal is to build muscle tissue - I promise you it matters more than the number of plates you can fit on the barbell or machine.

I’ll say it till I can no longer speak - growth is stimulus-dependent, not weight dependent ... don’t sacrifice the achieved stimulus for a heavier load in the logbook.

Or then there is the other side of things... 

Going up and down, back and forth, bouncing, moving with speed, and “just getting through it” is not enough! And it is what I see a lot of people doing far too often. And it will not get you the aesthetic results you want, or the strength you need!

And strength is a skill as much as it is an expression of force and power output ... don’t sacrifice your ability to sharpen your skill by getting yourself hurt and eliminating your ability to practice it. We need to be moving with intention in order to create a mind to the muscle and activating the fibres to create change!

FORM. MATTERS.So don’t just move the wait but move with INTENTION. Got questions? Send me a DM!

Soreness 🙅🏽‍♀️ growth
Soreness 🙅🏽‍♀️ you worked hard 
Soreness 🙅🏽‍♀️ you had a good training session
Soreness 🙅🏽‍♀️ something you should chase!

Wild mild soreness is fine, but no form of soreness should be seen as a main indicator or progress-or something that should be chased. 

Soreness and progress are not mutually exclusive.
And context is ALWAYS going to be and important part of the equation and consideration. 

Soreness will come largely from a new stimulus being placed on your body like
-a new weight (hitting a pr)
-adding a new tempo
-starting a new training program 
-trying a new exercise 
-returning after a break

But progress will come from maximizing your recovery, following a well rounded training program, and repeating the same movements with proper volume for a given amount of time, and keeping soreness to a minimum via your recovery, diet, and said program adherence. 

If you are sore all the time-you won’t be able to perform well. And performance goals will drive progress. 

I know it can feel good to feel sore-but if you really want to make progress it’s time to stop focusing on the more, and start focusing on the better!

I get it!
There’s someone at your gym whose using a machine, and when they’re done their set they’re just SITTING THERE staring off into space or possibly scrolling on their phone
what gives?
are they lazy? inconsiderate? taking their grand old time?
perhaps...
but they also may just be appropriately resting.

Taking time to rest between your sets is important and valuable, and it is one of the best things you can do when it comes to your strength and hypertrophy gains.
I would SO MUCH rather my clients sit and watch a couple tik toks, then do jumping jacks, burpees, planks, or whatever else between their sets.
Let your body have a moment to recover, regain some energy, and be able to push hard again in your next set.

How long you should be resting will depend on your goal, and the intention of your program. Heavier lifts require longer rest periods.

If you are new to strength training, a 2 minute rest period may feel like a LIFETIME-but i promise you, taking that rest will allow you to push progress in the long run.

ALSO: it is so perfectly normal to ask someone to work in on a machine or piece of equipment while they rest. Speak up! ask how many sets they have left, if they mind if you work in, and offer to help take off and put back on the weight they need if necessary. this is great gym etiquette, and opens the space for others to do so too.

MY GOAL: get strong. Be jacked. 
MY WORKOUTS: the basic sh*t over and over and over again.
•
I saw another post that shared this same message and showed this same journey and I wanted to make one of my own because I think the message is so important.
•
My workouts have been very similar to one another since 2017, but I’d say 2019 was the year I really put things into overdrive. That is the year I stopped taking group fitness classes, I stopped doing crazy finishers and hiit, I stopped basing my workouts around what I thought was fun or burned the most calories and I started getting serious about my strength training. 
•
Since that time-I have mostly stuck to the basic, foundational movement patterns and exercises. Variations of squat, lunge, hinge, thrust, push, and pull. I have done them over and over and over again and have gotten really good at them and really strong in them. 
•
My workouts don’t look crazy or entertaining-In fact they probably look pretty repetitive (they are). 
I never follow a program for less and 4 weeks and I never enter the gym without a plan and a goal for execution. 
I train with purpose and intent
•
My goals when it comes to training are to be strong and be jacked. And if you’re are the same-I cannot emphasize enough the importance of:
A plan
The need for repetition in that plan
And consistency in that plan. 
•
What is your goal? And are you truly training for it?

And that’s on not all exercises being created equally when it comes to applying progressive overload.
•
I am positive that you have had this same exact experience as me. 
Your weights are increasing on your compound lifts like your deadlifts, your squats, and your benchpress. But when it comes to your exercises like your dumbbell curl, your tricep extensions, and your lateral raises,The weight seems to stay the same forever.
•
WHAT GIVES
•
Know that this is totally normal. And the reason for that is because in your compound exercises like the ones I named above, you are going to have a large muscles and multiple muscle groups helping you to execute that exercise. 
For the exercises that tend to stay the same week over week month over month those exercises are more muscle isolated exercises. So you’ll be using only one muscle group and it would likely be a small one.
•
So, while we should always be striving for progressive overload in our workouts, know that not all progressive overload is created equally.

WHAT IS IT?
Creatine monohydrate is one of the most researached supplements in the industry.
Contrary to popular belief-creatine is NOT a steroid, and it actually is produced by, and exists naturally in our bodies already.

WHAT DOES IT DO?
Creatine helps your body produce more energy by increasing your ATP (adenosine triphosphate) stores.
Your body naturally produces ATP in the skeletal muscle and brain and is also consumed in foods like meat and fish
however it may not always be enough for increased gym performance.

ATP helps to provide you with energy for high intensity, explosive, and powerful movements, and increased creatine stores can enhance the body’s resistance to fatique

So more creatine = more ATP = more energy output = better performance in the gym = potential for more muscle growth

HOW DO YOU TAKE IT?
Creatine is an accumulative supplement-meaning-you take it daily to gain the benefits it holds.
Timing is not the most important factor when it comes to creatine-but you may find it slightly more helpful to take prior to or during your workout.
5g/day is the serving size

BUT DOESNT IT MAKE YOU GAIN WEIGHT?
Creatine draws more water into your muscles-which will help them appear fuller and bigger.
This may cause a slight spike on the scale when you first start taking it.
Know that this is temporary increased water retention and NOT fat gain.

FIX YOUR SH!T: Don’t thrust at the top of your squat 🔥

While your coach may instruct you to “squeeze your glutes” at the top of a squat-most likely in an effort to keep you out of an anterior tilt, often times this cue gets misunderstood, and we see the client actively push their hips further forward.

Other times, clients end up squeezing their glutes at the top to give themselves this moment of finality in their squat-which isnt necessary.

In a squat, the top of the movement is relatively unloaded for the glutes. Glutes are utilized heavily during the bottom two-thirds of the range of motion. 

Pushing the hips forward, or thrusting, at the top of the squat is not optimal nor necessary, and may actually cause increased stress to the lumbar spine. 

How?

❌ Don’t thrust your hips at the top of the squat
❌ Driving your hips into excessive posterior pelvic tilt, creating lumbar flexion, or pushing the hips forward too much, moving the spine into
HYPEREXTENSION:
❌ introduces risk of injury, puts the weight behind you and no longer over your center of gravity causes you to lose tension in your core and back.

INSTEAD of what is should be:

✅ Think about your pelvis as a bucket of water. tilt too far back and the water falls out, thrust too far front and the water falls out. we want to keep the water in the bucket by keeping hips neutral.

You can’t just move. You must move WELL.

Consistency is king, but progressive overload is queen 👑. 

Without challenging yourself and pushing your limits, you won’t see the gains you’re looking for.

Progressive overload is an important concept you hear talked about all the time in relation to your strength and body composition goals, and it refers to the concept of doing more over time.

However, so often progressive overload is looked at as only being able to lift more weight.
and while adding more load to your lifts is one version of progressive overload, it is important to know that growth is STIMULUS dependent, not WEIGHT dependent-and there are multiple ways to apply progressive overload to your body and your lifts without adding additional load.

If you continue to use the same weight, resistance, or lifting methods over time, your muscles will eventually adapt to the stress, and you will plateau in terms of strength and muscle gains. 

This is why progressive overload is crucial for continued progress and improvement.

Along the way, there are some challenges you’ll naturally face—here’s how I handle them!

1. Fluctuations-I believe it’s NORMAL to see your numbers on a scale, strength, and your body fluctuate and vary day to day. Progress isn’t linear, and as long as you’re trending the right way and staying consistent, you’re ahead of the game.
2. Food restrictions—I don’t restrict any foods or any food groups! This one may shock some of you, but a donut every once in a while won’t kill you (or your progress).

4. Cardio is not my fundamental method to lose fat. I rely heavily on weight training and better nutrition to focus more on building muscle and seeing results.
5. Cycle syncing—I don’t train differently based on my menstrual cycle, but I do stay in tune with my body and listen to its needs and understand my workout may be a bit different during certain times of the month.

Want to grow your 🍑 this year? Here’s my top strength training tips to get you there throughout your workout! 

1. Repetition, repetition, repetition. Repetition allows your muscles to experience the same stress repeatedly, leading to progressive overload, which is the gradual increase in resistance or workload. Progressive overload is necessary for muscle growth because it forces your muscles to adapt and become stronger in order to handle the increased stress.
2. Pushing towards failure. When you continue to push yourself until you cannot perform any more repetitions with good form, you are subjecting your muscles to the highest possible level of stress, which can lead to greater muscle damage and subsequent adaptation. Additionally, pushing to near failure can help you develop mental toughness and discipline, which are important qualities in any fitness or performance endeavor!
3. Moving with intent and tension. It’s not just about what you do, but how you do it! Lifting with full tension helps to stimulate the maximum number of muscle fibers within a muscle group, leading to greater muscle activation. This type of lifting causes an increase in metabolic stress on the muscles, which is a key factor in triggering muscle growth.

before we jump in-this is what I am doing to still train my lower body and stay on track with my goals while I recover from a minor lower back tweak. 
While these modifications and tid bits of advice may work for you, some also may not. Consult with your PT.
All of these suggestions will require near-perfect execution! So as always, I recommend working with a professional to get your form checked, and make sure you are lifting WELL first and foremost.

1) CORE WORK: specifically, exercises that strengthen the transverse abdominals-the deep core muscles. these muscles are the most important when it comes to supporting the lower back, and creating a solid brace for the rest of your body to move around

2) STABILITY: the more stable of an environment you are lifting in, the safer that lift will be. We can create stability via our own body by properly breathing and bracing-however, machines are also a great option, as they create a lot of that support for you.

3) RANGE OF MOTION: specifically for my squat and deadlift. the lower you go in these moves, the more stress they will put on the lower back. And while “stress” is not always a bad thing, while in the midst of recovering, it isn’t our top choice. I reduce my range of motion here to still work similar muscle groups and movement patterns, but in a safer environment

4) LOAD: you cannot and should not lift as heavy or as hard during injury as when you are full on healthy. That doesn’t mean you have to stop lifting completely! Choose a weight that allows you to work pain free.

Welcome back to another segment of Fix Your Sh!t. 

Today’s topic will save your lower back from a lifetime of aches, pains, and deadlifts done dirty. 

Let’s get to fixin’. 

​​ For those of you who are feeling any lower back pain during your deadlifts, the likely culprit is the way you are pulling the bar off the ground, when instead, you should be thinking about your deadlifts as a push movement, where you’re thinking about pushing the ground away from you. 

​​ DON’T lead deadlifts with your hips or straighten your legs until the very end of the deadlift. 

​​ DO keep your knees and hips where they are until the barbell is at knee-height, and then pull your hips through.

​​ DON’T put tension on your lower back, at any point during your deadlift.

​​ DO start your deadlift with a neutral spine while engaging your hamstrings, quads, and glutes, using these muscles to do the heavy lifting. 

​​ Give these corrections a go and your back will thank you. For more guidance, schedule a coaching call and join our LWL community.

🚨HOT TIP TIME🚨
For your single arm rows-think about rowing BACK-towards your belly button, back pocket, hip-whatever cue helps you there
Instead of
Rowing straight up to your chest. 
We should see the dumbbell make a little swoop motion, instead of a straight line from the bottom of the movement to the top. 

It’s easy to tell which you are doing by the angle of your arm-which is best observed by filming yourself perform your sets!

If the angle of your arm is less than 90 degrees-there is a good chance you are using a lot of trap and bicep to perform your row, and not so much lat-as is its intention.

It’s not about what you do between Christmas and New Year’s, but what you do between New Year’s and Christmas.

What you do on a daily basis–your habits and your routine–matters more than what you do every once in a while. Don’t let guilt get in the way of being present during big life events, holidays, and time off. Build habits that you look forward to picking up again once you settle back into your routine.

I know that every bit counts. Just because I can’t hit my protein goals 100% of the time doesn’t mean I didn’t pay attention to my protein intake. Just because I don’t have access to a full gym doesn’t mean I skipped my workouts completely–we do what we can. Control the controllables. 

I know that the important part is just getting back into the regularly scheduled program. I am organized and prepared around my diet and training, so I know how to slip back into it with ease. Nothing comes as a stressful surprise.

I have been committed to a program, learned the protocols, tracked muscle growth and fat loss for long enough that I know what matters and what makes the biggest differences. 

Going through this process has allowed me more mental freedom over the holidays and life in general, because I’m not sweating the small stuff. I know the work that counts the most, and know that it is within the life I already have to make it happen.

Feeling guilty about enjoying time off is so 2023. Here’s to normalizing balance and consistency in 2024.

4. Glute med kickbacks: similar to above-say what you will-but after adding these in regularly, my booty is looking more shelf like everyday.
